Pass the garden, for each flower try to form L (check 4 points in diagonals).  
When you form L (with at least 1 unvisited flower) count it as a unique L and mark its flowers as visited.

You check the 4 adjacent diagonals for each flower, searching for L. 
How you would for the center flower in image above, I believe.

You want to form L with upper/bottom or left/right diagonals 

Something like I'm at (x, y)
check (x - 1, y - 1) (x, y) (x - 1, y + 1) <- two upper diagonals
check (x + 1, y - 1) (x, y) (x + 1, y + 1) <- two bottom diagonals
check (x - 1, y - 1) (x, y) (x + 1, y - 1) <- two left diagonals
check (x + 1, y - 1) (x, y) (x + 1, y + 1) <- two right diagonals
of course, make sure you don't break bounds.

If out of those 3 coordinates, at least 1 is unvisited. That would be a unique L, so count it and mark all as visited.

Think you can do all this on the fly as you "seed the garden" and just keep a dictionary of visited flowers that is all


